column17: Assibilation of *tˊ to *c and of *dˊ to *dz
column26: The change of *i to *ь and of *u to *ъ
column30: Lengthening of short vowels in unaccented word forms
column34: The first jotation and Kortlandt's compensatory lengthening
column44: The loss of the acute tone
column48: The change of *štˊ to *št and of *ždˊ to *žd
column54: The change of word-initial *t to *k before oral non-velar plosives
column55: The change of *β to *u before consonants and in word-final position
column56: The change of *ь to *a and of *ь̄ to *ā
column57: Lengthening of *e and *o before word-final *n and *r
column61: The change of *ě̄ to *ɩē and of *ě to *ɩe (or *e)
column63: The change of syllabic *l̥ to *u and of syllabic *l̥̄ to *ū
column64: The change of *čr to *cr and of *čr̄ to *cr̄
column68: Lengthening of vowels before sonorant-consonant sequences and before word-final *j
column69: The loss of the neo-acute tone

column2: The velar obstruents *k, *g, *x changed to *tˊ, *dˊ, *ś if they were immediately preceded by *i, *ī, or *j, or by sequences consisting of *i and a nasal *n
column3: Back vowels were fronted after the palatal consonants *j, *tˊ,*dˊ, and *ś: *u > *i, *ū > *ī, *a > *e, *ā > *ē
column4: Tautosyllabic sequences of vowel and *w or *j were monophthongized: *aw, *āw, *ew, *ēw > *ọ̄; *aj, *āj > *ē; *ej, *ēj > *ẹ̄ > *ī
column5: *ē was backened to *ā after the palatal consonants *j, *č, *dž, *š, *tˊ, *dˊ, *ś
column7: The bilabial glide *w changed to the bilabial fricative *β
column8: The velar obstruents *k, *g, *x changed to *tˊ, *dˊ, *ś if they were immediately followed by a front vowel resulting from monophthongization or by a sequence consisting of *w and a front vowel resulting from monophthongization
column9: A lateral *l was inserted between the labial consonants *p, *b, *m, *w and an immediately following glide *j
column10: Palatal *ś resulting from one of the two Common Slavic palatalizations (§§ 1, 8) changed to palatalized *s
column11: Tautosyllabic word-initial sequences *ar˙-, *al˙- bearing the acute tone changed to *rā˙, *lā˙
column12: The acute tone was dropped on unaccented syllables except for the first post-tonic syllable
column13: The accent shifted one syllable to the right from non-acute syllables
column14: The sequence *kt changed to *k't' unless it was immediately followed by a back vowel
column15: The sequences *kt, *xt lost their velar component and changed to *t
column16: The long high back vowel *ū was delabialized to *ȳ
column17: The palatals *tˊ and *dˊ, resulting from the Third and the Second palatalizations, assibilated to *c and *dz, respectively
column18: The long vowel *ō, resulting from the monophthongization of *aw, *āw, *ew, *ēw, was raised to *ū
column19: The affricate *dž, resulting from the pre-Proto-Slavic First palatalization, changed to *ž
column20: In sequences of dental plosives and laterals, the plosives were lost: *tl, *dl > *l
column21: Tautosyllabic sequences of non-high vowel + liquid that had not been affected by the first liquid metathesis (§ 10) were metathesized: *ar, *er, *al, *el > *rā, *rē, *lā, *lē
column22: Word-initial vowels *ā, *e, *ē,  and *i received a prothetic glide *j
column23: Non-high long vowels were shortened before tautosyllabic *n: *ān, *ēn > *an, *en
column26: The short high vowels *i and *u changed to the so-called jers *ь and *ъ, respectively
column27: A jer (*ъ, *ь) was inserted into word-final sequences of consonant + sonorant + jer
column28: Tautosyllabic sequences *ъr, *ьr, *ъl, *ьl changed to long syllabic liquids *r̥̄, *l̥̄, and tautosyllabic sequences *rъ, *rь, *lъ *lь changed to short syllabic liquids r̥, *l̥ (in examples, the underscore ring "˳" is written only if it does not colide with other diacritics)
column29: Tautosyllabic sequences of front vowel + nasal consonant changed to *ę̄ and tautosyllabic sequences of back vowel + nasal consonant change to *ǭ: *en, *eń, *em, *ьn, *ьń, *ьm > *ę̄; *on, *oń, *om, *ъn, *ъń, *ъm > *ǭ
column30: In unaccented word forms, short vowels were lengthened before word-final syllables ending in a jer (*ъ, *ь)
column31: Unaccented word forms received an accent on their first syllable; if the word form was preceived by proclitics, the first syllable of the accentual unit received the accent; if the word form was followed by an enclitic, the enclitic received the accent regardless of whether it was preceded by proclitics
column33: Two vowels which were separated from each other by the glide *j and had the same height or a height that differed by one degree (there were for degrees of vowel height at the relevant stage) merged into a long vowel; an acute tone on the first of the contracted syllables was lost; if the second of the contracted syllables was accented the resulting long vowel received a neo-acute tone which in the present study is marked by a mid-level dot "·"; if three consecutive syllables are separated only by a glide *j only the last two were affected by contraction
column34:
The sequences *tj, *dj, *sj, *zj, *rj, *lj, *nj, *čj, and *žj were "jotated" to *tʹ, *dʹ, *š, *ž, *rʼ, *lʹ, *ń, *č, and *ž; if a *Cj sequence was preceded by *s or *z, the latter were affected by jotation as well; as a result of the loss of the glide *j, a short following syllable was lengthened; this lengthening was later on undone by several analogical processes but left an indirect trace in the accent shift according to Ivšić's first law (§ 36)
t, n, č i Ž
column35: The sequences *ḱtˊ, *x́tˊ, resulting from the change of *kt, *xt to *ḱtˊ, *x́tˊ (§ 13), were simplified to *tˊ
column36: The affricate *dz, resulting from the change *dʹ > *dz (§ 16), changed to the fricative *z
column37: The accent shifted from a long syllable not bearing the acute or neoacute tone by one syllable to the left; if the newly accented syllable was long, it received a neoacute tone
column38: The accent shifted from a jer (*ъ, *ь) by one syllable to the left; if the newly accented syllable was long, it received a neoacute tone
column39: The unrounded back vowel *ȳ was fronted to *ī
column40: The back jers *ъ, *ъ̄  merged with the front jers *ь, *ь̄
column41: Word-initial *jь- changed to *i-; the resulting high front vowel was always short
column42: Pretonic long vowels were shortened if they were followed by two or more morae (jers = half a mora, short vowels = one mora, long vowels = two morae)
column43: In words consisting of four or more syllables that bore the accent on the first syllable, long vowels in the second syllable were shortened
column44: Long vowels bearing the acute tone were shortened; in the course of the shortening, the acute tone was lost
column45: Apart from vowels bearing the neoacute tone, long vowels were shortened in words with three or more syllables which did not have a jer (*ъ, ь*) in the paenultima
column46: A voiced dental plosive was inserted into the sequence *žr: *žr > *ždr
column47: A jer was inserted into sequences of consonant + sonorant + jer that had arisen after the first jer-epenthesis (§ 26) as a result of sound change or analogical change
column48: The sequences *štʹ, ždʹ changed to *št, žd
column49: The two nasal vowels were denasalized: *ę, *ę̄ > *e, *ē; *ǫ, *ǭ > *u, *ū
column50: When counting consecutive syllables containing jers, *ь was lost in odd syllable (so-called weak position); if a weak jer was stressed, the accent shifted to the immediately following syllable
column51: Word-initial sequences consisting of sonorant + fricative were metathesized
column52: In consonant clusters resulting from the loss of weak jers (§ 49), several assimilations with regard to the place and manner of articulation occurred
column53: Complex consonant clusters resulting from the loss of weak jers (§ 49) were simplified
column54: The voiceless dental plosive *t changed to its velar counterpart *k before oral non-velar plosives
column55: The bilabial fricative *β changed to *u before consonants and in word-final position
column56: Jers which had not been lost as a result of the loss of weak jers (§ 49) changed to *a: *ь, *ь̄ > *a, *ā
column57: The vowels *e and *o were lengthened before word-final *-n and *-r
column58: Jat *ě, *ě̄ was raised to *i, *ī before a tautosyllabic lateral *l: *ěl, *ě̄l > *il, *īl
column59: Jat *ě was raised to *i before the glide *j: *ěj > *ij
column60: A lateral *l was inserted into sequences consisting of a labial consonant *p, *b, *m, *v and the glide *j that had arisen as a result of the loss of weak jers (§ 49): *pj, *bj, *mj, *vj > *plj, *blj, *mlj, *vlj
column61: Jat *ě, *ě̄  diphthongized to *ɩe, *ɩē unless it was preceded by *j or a sequence of consonant + *r in which case it changed to *e
column62: Palatalized *r’, resulting from jotation (§ 33) was depalatalized to *r
column64: Before rhotics (syllabic or non-syllabic), *č changed to *c: *čr > *cr; *čr̥ > *cr̥; *čr̥̄ > *cr̥̄
column66: As a result of the loss of weak jers (§ 43) and the second l-epenthesis (§ 59), new sequences of dental consonant + j arose; these sequences the target to a second jotation: *tj > *tʹ, *tʹj > *tʹ, *dj > *dʹ, *dʹj > *dʹ, *stj > *štʹ, *zdj > *zdʹ, *lj > *jʹ, *slj > *šlʹ, *nj > *ń, *lɩe > *lʹe,  *nɩe > *ńe; *jt > *tʹ, *jd > *dʹ
column67: Non-syllabic *ɩ in the diphthong *ɩe changed to *j
column68: Vowels were lengthened before syllable-final sonorants and *j
column69: The neo-acute tone merged with the falling tone
column70: The accent was shifted by one syllalbe to the left; newly accented syllables received a rising tone which, in this study, is marked by a dot on the line (V̄., V.)
column71: The bilabial fricative *β changed to the labiodental *v
column72: The palatal plosives *tˊ, *dˊ, resulting from the second Jotation, changed to the affricates *ć, *đ
